VILLAGERS have helped police in arresting three suspects, aged between 26 and 30, for the theft of copper cables worth R3 000. The arrests were made at Ga-Magongoa Village in Ga-Mashashane outside Polokwane, Limpopo, on Wednesday, 26 January. This after police received a tip-off from villagers about the suspects and quickly reacted. One of them was found in possession of copper cables to the street value of R3 000 and a bolt cutter. The three are allegedly a group of criminals that have been tormenting communities in and around the area following several reported cases of cable theft and vandalism. Limpopo police spokesman Brigadier Motlafela Mojapelo said further investigations were conducted, which led to the arrest two more suspects for attempted cable theft. “In a concerted effort to fight cable theft across the province, a partnership between police and community members resulted in the arrest of three suspects for alleged theft in Ga-Magongoa,” said Mojapelo. He said the suspects are expected to appear before the Seshego Magistrates Court on Friday, 28 January, facing charges of possession of suspected stolen property and damage to infrastructure. “Police investigations continue,” he said. Provincial commissioner Lieutenant-General Thembi Hadebe thanked the villagers for working with police in the fight against crime. “I urged them to continue sharing information about any suspicious activities by contacting CrimeStop at 08600 10111 or their nearest police station,” said Hadebe.